  <div class="container">
    <h2>1. Example: A Simple Music‑QA Demo</h2>
    <p>
      This code cell shows how a basic question‑answering system over musical metadata
      could work. You can edit the code or question and run it directly in your browser.
    </p>

    <div class="cell-block thebe-cell" data-executable="true" data-language="python">
      <pre data-executable="true" data-language="python">
# Simple Music-QA demo
metadata = {
    "tempo": 95,
    "key": "A minor",
    "instrumentation": ["violin", "laouto", "voice"],
}

question = "What is the key of the piece?"

if "key" in question.lower():
    answer = metadata["key"]
else:
    answer = "I don't know yet, but future models will!"

answer
      </pre>
    </div>

    <h2>2. Try Out a Gesture‑Audio Relationship Example</h2>
    <p>
      Modify the numbers to see how gesture amplitude could relate to dynamic level.
      This is a toy example to illustrate multimodal reasoning.
    </p>

    <div class="cell-block thebe-cell" data-executable="true" data-language="python">
      <pre data-executable="true" data-language="python">
# Gesture–audio toy model
import math

gesture_amplitude = 0.6  # change this value (0–1)
audio_dynamic = round(gesture_amplitude * 100)

f"Estimated dynamic level: {audio_dynamic} (0–100 scale)"
      </pre>
    </div>

    <h2>3. Explore Multimodal Inputs</h2>
    <p>
      This cell prints how a hypothetical system might select which modality to use
      based on the question — inspired by Paper V.
    </p>

    <div class="cell-block thebe-cell" data-executable="true" data-language="python">
      <pre data-executable="true" data-language="python">
# Simple modality selector
question = "How fast is the performer moving?"

if "moving" in question.lower() or "gesture" in question.lower():
    modality = "motion capture"
elif "sound" in question.lower() or "loud" in question.lower():
    modality = "audio"
else:
    modality = "text or metadata"

f"Selected modality: {modality}"
      </pre>
    </div>
  </div>

